WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.180 --> 00:00:02.193
- Okay, so let's get started.

00:00:04.099 --> 00:00:05.510
A lot of people on Instagram.

00:00:05.510 --> 00:00:10.063
So, okay, so muscle confusion theory,

00:00:11.414 --> 00:00:14.360
I think this came about for a
couple of different reasons.

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:18.712
One is that people notice
when they drastically change

00:00:18.712 --> 00:00:23.010
their exercise program, they get sore.

00:00:23.010 --> 00:00:27.760
And the question is does
soreness equal growth?

00:00:27.760 --> 00:00:28.880
Is that gains?

00:00:28.880 --> 00:00:32.360
Is that something that we
need to go looking for?

00:00:32.360 --> 00:00:34.633
Do I need to, I'm adjusting my,

00:00:35.510 --> 00:00:38.700
do we need to go looking for soreness?

00:00:38.700 --> 00:00:40.670
Of course the answer is no.

00:00:40.670 --> 00:00:43.570
Soreness has nothing to do with gains.

00:00:43.570 --> 00:00:48.570
There's never been any
evidence that that was a thing.

00:00:49.321 --> 00:00:52.360
In fact, micro tears in muscle

00:00:52.360 --> 00:00:55.550
are highly associated with soreness.

00:00:55.550 --> 00:00:58.930
Marathon runners and cyclists
have the most micro tears

00:00:58.930 --> 00:01:01.620
of any type of athlete.

00:01:01.620 --> 00:01:03.760
They don't build big anything.

00:01:03.760 --> 00:01:08.200
So why get excited about muscle soreness?

00:01:08.200 --> 00:01:11.400
And I think the other thing
was Arnold Schwarzenegger

00:01:11.400 --> 00:01:16.400
was a big promoter of shocking
the muscle into growth.

00:01:21.470 --> 00:01:23.070
That's not a thing.

00:01:23.070 --> 00:01:25.790
So we all love Arnold Schwarzenegger,

00:01:25.790 --> 00:01:28.890
however, that's still not a thing.

00:01:28.890 --> 00:01:33.890
So what we need to look at
is what you're trying to do

00:01:34.350 --> 00:01:37.270
to the central nervous
system when you expose load

00:01:37.270 --> 00:01:38.680
to the body, whether you lift a weight

00:01:38.680 --> 00:01:40.370
or even if you're running
or something like that.

00:01:40.370 --> 00:01:42.320
Why does adaptation happen?

00:01:42.320 --> 00:01:45.060
You give a clear signal to
the central nervous system.

00:01:45.060 --> 00:01:48.987
Well, the central nervous
system makes a determination,

00:01:48.987 --> 00:01:51.800
"We don't have enough of X."

00:01:51.800 --> 00:01:54.117
Like, "We don't have enough bicep,

00:01:54.117 --> 00:01:55.967
"so we're gonna work really hard

00:01:55.967 --> 00:01:58.070
"to build more bicep tissue."

00:01:58.070 --> 00:02:01.280
So to do that, there's certain strategies.

00:02:01.280 --> 00:02:04.050
And so, like, when you look

00:02:04.050 --> 00:02:07.010
at what the American College
of Sports Medicine has done,

00:02:07.010 --> 00:02:09.413
and when they put out a position paper,

00:02:09.413 --> 00:02:13.430
that means they've considered
hundreds of studies,

00:02:13.430 --> 00:02:18.130
potentially, and looked at
people testing muscle confusion

00:02:18.130 --> 00:02:23.130
versus regular standard
lifting with an aim towards

00:02:24.194 --> 00:02:26.460
having a greater output every time.

00:02:26.460 --> 00:02:28.800
I don't wanna call that
progressive resistance

00:02:28.800 --> 00:02:31.820
because there's another, sort of,

00:02:31.820 --> 00:02:34.540
poor use of progressive resistance

00:02:34.540 --> 00:02:37.240
that we're gonna talk about
later in another video.

00:02:37.240 --> 00:02:42.240
But ultimately, whether
you bench press X-weight

00:02:42.330 --> 00:02:46.490
for 10 reps and then the
next workout you can do that

00:02:46.490 --> 00:02:49.970
same thing for 11
repetitions, you got stronger.

00:02:49.970 --> 00:02:51.790
That's a greater output,

00:02:51.790 --> 00:02:56.690
and so that means that you
have increased your strength,

00:02:56.690 --> 00:02:58.030
so grown muscle.

00:02:58.030 --> 00:03:03.030
So when that happens,
especially when sticking

00:03:03.660 --> 00:03:08.660
to the same program, you're
going to have a greater amount

00:03:08.960 --> 00:03:11.280
of success than if you're just haphazardly

00:03:11.280 --> 00:03:14.110
doing one thing versus the other.

00:03:14.110 --> 00:03:16.470
And one of the reasons
that might be happening

00:03:16.470 --> 00:03:20.523
is that focuses you on skill building,

00:03:21.520 --> 00:03:24.530
except only one time,

00:03:24.530 --> 00:03:26.440
because, like, okay, let's
say you do a chest workout,

00:03:26.440 --> 00:03:29.930
pushups, and then your next
thing is all based on flys,

00:03:29.930 --> 00:03:33.780
and then the next thing is
all based on one-arm work

00:03:33.780 --> 00:03:36.223
or cross-body work or something like that,

00:03:38.240 --> 00:03:41.220
you are not really building a skill.

00:03:41.220 --> 00:03:44.920
You're just haphazardly
doing one thing or another,

00:03:44.920 --> 00:03:47.080
and then you go to something else

00:03:47.080 --> 00:03:49.800
and you're haphazardly doing that too.

00:03:49.800 --> 00:03:54.267
And so ultimately, it
just makes you, kind of,

00:03:54.267 --> 00:03:57.320
evenly bad at everything.

00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:59.420
You're not building
any skills out of that,

00:03:59.420 --> 00:04:04.420
and it's not optimum for
muscular growth or performance.

00:04:05.250 --> 00:04:08.580
Think about, or part of the reason

00:04:08.580 --> 00:04:11.060
the American College of
Sports Medicine looked at this

00:04:11.060 --> 00:04:13.860
was when it comes to athletic training

00:04:13.860 --> 00:04:15.510
for a very specific purpose,

00:04:15.510 --> 00:04:17.660
so very elite athletes,

00:04:17.660 --> 00:04:20.097
you wouldn't take an
elite swimmer and say,

00:04:20.097 --> 00:04:22.137
"All right, now what we want you to do

00:04:22.137 --> 00:04:24.787
"is become a great cyclist

00:04:24.787 --> 00:04:27.387
"because that's really gonna
help you in the water."

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:31.313
Like, nobody would do that, nobody.

00:04:32.210 --> 00:04:34.877
So ultimately, if you
wanna be a better swimmer,

00:04:34.877 --> 00:04:36.173
you've gotta swim.

00:04:37.090 --> 00:04:42.090
And you have to stay
focused on what you want.

00:04:42.840 --> 00:04:47.270
So for what I'm encouraging people to do

00:04:47.270 --> 00:04:49.890
is be as strong and as lean as possible.

00:04:49.890 --> 00:04:53.810
Those are two goals that we
can get to pretty easily.

00:04:53.810 --> 00:04:58.810
And, by using the right
triggers and the right stimuli

00:04:59.560 --> 00:05:01.110
for the central nervous system.

00:05:01.110 --> 00:05:04.680
So when you show that,
the central nervous system

00:05:04.680 --> 00:05:08.193
that you have a deficit of
bicep issue or trapezius tissue,

00:05:09.990 --> 00:05:14.853
and you first go to a fatigue
from a myofibril standpoint,

00:05:14.853 --> 00:05:16.680
then a sarcoplasmic standpoint,

00:05:16.680 --> 00:05:18.830
meaning first, the amount
of contractile protein,

00:05:18.830 --> 00:05:20.230
the actual tissue there,

00:05:20.230 --> 00:05:22.320
and then the amount of
fuel held in the tissue.

00:05:22.320 --> 00:05:24.643
You ram that all into one experience.

00:05:24.643 --> 00:05:27.157
The central nervous system
doesn't have a choice.

00:05:27.157 --> 00:05:28.962
"We've just gotta build more traps."

00:05:28.962 --> 00:05:30.390
That's it.

00:05:30.390 --> 00:05:35.390
And both stimuli manifests
in both types of growth,

00:05:35.700 --> 00:05:37.270
and the growth can happen very quickly

00:05:37.270 --> 00:05:42.270
if you really clearly
fatigue that musculature.

00:05:44.190 --> 00:05:48.350
Now so what else?

00:05:48.350 --> 00:05:52.130
One of the justifications for,
like, mixing up your workout

00:05:52.130 --> 00:05:54.280
is when people say they're bored.

00:05:54.280 --> 00:05:56.237
I hear that from trainers.

00:05:56.237 --> 00:05:58.415
"Oh, I wanna keep my
clients from being bored."

00:05:58.415 --> 00:06:02.515
Well, there's, to me, there's effective

00:06:02.515 --> 00:06:04.500
and not effective; right?

00:06:04.500 --> 00:06:07.920
Like, so you wouldn't brush
your teeth with your socks

00:06:07.920 --> 00:06:10.930
because you're really bored
of your toothbrush; right?

00:06:10.930 --> 00:06:14.410
Like, you just wouldn't do that.

00:06:14.410 --> 00:06:15.870
You use a toothbrush every day.

00:06:15.870 --> 00:06:17.406
So is it exciting?

00:06:17.406 --> 00:06:18.870
I don't know.

00:06:18.870 --> 00:06:22.480
I don't particularly feel like
high-fiving a lot of people

00:06:22.480 --> 00:06:26.470
when I brush my teeth, but, you know,

00:06:26.470 --> 00:06:28.100
probably feel a little
bit better after I do it.

00:06:28.100 --> 00:06:31.599
But I feel a lot better
after I do my X3 workout,

00:06:31.599 --> 00:06:36.599
so I apologize if the proper
program seems monotonous.

00:06:40.200 --> 00:06:41.940
It will be monotonous,

00:06:41.940 --> 00:06:45.450
but you're not doing it for
the sake of getting a workout.

00:06:45.450 --> 00:06:46.770
That's another thing that,

00:06:46.770 --> 00:06:48.480
man, I just wanna throw
somebody off a building

00:06:48.480 --> 00:06:50.470
when somebody says, "Hey, can
you get a workout from that?"

00:06:50.470 --> 00:06:53.420
It's, like, what does that
even mean, get a workout?

00:06:53.420 --> 00:06:58.420
That's just, that's the
vehicle, not the destination.

00:06:59.220 --> 00:07:02.100
That's just completely
confusing what your objective is

00:07:02.100 --> 00:07:05.468
and, I think, basically, foolish.

00:07:05.468 --> 00:07:07.420
Get a workout.

00:07:07.420 --> 00:07:09.360
It's to trigger result,

00:07:09.360 --> 00:07:12.660
and you're always driving
towards triggering that result.

00:07:12.660 --> 00:07:17.060
So working out, it's not entertainment.

00:07:17.060 --> 00:07:19.460
You, the entertainment, the enjoyment,

00:07:19.460 --> 00:07:23.330
is being stronger and
leaner everywhere you go.

00:07:23.330 --> 00:07:25.840
Having better posture everywhere you go.

00:07:25.840 --> 00:07:27.800
That's what you enjoy.

00:07:27.800 --> 00:07:29.057
And for the people who say,

00:07:29.057 --> 00:07:31.057
"Oh, yeah, strength
training is hard, it hurts,"

00:07:31.057 --> 00:07:33.150
it's just, like, suck it up.

00:07:33.150 --> 00:07:37.370
You don't have a whole
lot of time to commit

00:07:37.370 --> 00:07:40.760
to getting that work in that
very brief period of time

00:07:40.760 --> 00:07:42.580
and pulling those triggers in the body

00:07:42.580 --> 00:07:45.430
and doing the protocol the right way.

00:07:45.430 --> 00:07:47.730
And then you just wait
for the growth to happen,

00:07:47.730 --> 00:07:49.090
because it will.

00:07:49.090 --> 00:07:51.760
So other things I just wanna recap,

00:07:51.760 --> 00:07:55.090
and I think we're just
about good on this subject.

00:07:55.090 --> 00:07:58.450
I don't wanna beat a dead horse here.

00:07:58.450 --> 00:08:00.610
Oh, I did also say the whole, like,

00:08:00.610 --> 00:08:03.387
workout of the day thing
that Cross Fitters do,

00:08:03.387 --> 00:08:07.890
that's the same, kind of,
like, muscle confusion theory.

00:08:07.890 --> 00:08:11.720
And ultimately, like, workouts work.

00:08:11.720 --> 00:08:13.740
Like, somebody who does pushups one day

00:08:13.740 --> 00:08:15.330
and does something else another day,

00:08:15.330 --> 00:08:19.160
it's not like they're gonna
get nothing out of it.

00:08:19.160 --> 00:08:22.750
They just won't get as much out of that,

00:08:22.750 --> 00:08:25.735
as opposed to really sticking
with something consistently

00:08:25.735 --> 00:08:28.070
and applying it and analyzing it,

00:08:28.070 --> 00:08:29.450
analyzing it, and analyzing it,

00:08:29.450 --> 00:08:31.140
and trying to get a little bit more,

00:08:31.140 --> 00:08:31.973
and a little bit more,

00:08:31.973 --> 00:08:34.370
and a little bit more out of it each time.

00:08:34.370 --> 00:08:37.350
Then you've gotta measure in your head

00:08:37.350 --> 00:08:39.930
or if you're writing it
down or making a video

00:08:39.930 --> 00:08:42.116
for yourself so you can critique it later.

00:08:42.116 --> 00:08:47.116
Like, all those things are
with an eye towards progress,

00:08:47.980 --> 00:08:51.750
not just shuffling the
deck and doing some stuff.

00:08:51.750 --> 00:08:55.640
So workout of the day,
yeah, sorry, thumbs down.

00:08:55.640 --> 00:08:56.890
You know, wouldn't do it.

00:08:57.780 --> 00:09:00.680
So when, ultimately,

00:09:00.680 --> 00:09:05.680
I did a podcast yesterday
where the interviewer

00:09:06.960 --> 00:09:08.845
was asking me some questions about, like,

00:09:08.845 --> 00:09:11.067
"God, you're throwing a lot
of ideas that are really

00:09:11.067 --> 00:09:15.030
"upsetting to the
strength-training industry."

00:09:15.030 --> 00:09:15.863
Well, you know what?

00:09:15.863 --> 00:09:17.810
The strength-training industry

00:09:17.810 --> 00:09:19.440
isn't really doing that great.

00:09:19.440 --> 00:09:20.430
When I walk down the street,

00:09:20.430 --> 00:09:22.113
who looks like they exercise?

00:09:23.410 --> 00:09:25.570
Nobody, that's who.

00:09:25.570 --> 00:09:27.420
Basically, nobody.

00:09:27.420 --> 00:09:29.910
So why are people just grabbing a hold

00:09:29.910 --> 00:09:31.760
of some many of these principals

00:09:31.760 --> 00:09:36.760
that you can just do a Google
Scholar or Medline search

00:09:37.100 --> 00:09:39.495
on and realize that they're not real?

00:09:39.495 --> 00:09:41.610
And then on top of that,

00:09:41.610 --> 00:09:44.105
people are so emotionally
tied to these things

00:09:44.105 --> 00:09:47.040
that obviously aren't working.

00:09:47.040 --> 00:09:48.753
So why be tied to it?

